Headlines.Headline: LabCorp 3Q Net Down 4.1% On Higher Operating Costs; Guidance Raised

PARAGRAPH.#text: Laboratory Corp. of America Holdings' LH third-quarter profit fell 4.1% as increased costs outweighed higher testing volume. The company raised its adjusted earnings guidance for the year to $6.28 to $6.33 a share and narrowed its revenue growth to 10.5% to 11%. In July, it forecast adjusted earnings of $6.17 to $6.32 a share and revenue growth of 9.5% to 11.5%. The provider of medical-testing services has seen revenue improve in the past few quarters, but testing volume had fallen amid a drop in doctor visits, as consumers have tried to curb medical costs.

Headlines.Author: Jennifer Corbett
Headlines.Headline: FDA Officials Not Sure Agency Will Approve Direct-To-Consumer Genetic Tests

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Friday.) By Jennifer Corbett Dooren Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--Top Food and Drug Administration officials suggested they would set a high, if not impossible, bar for companies seeking to sell genetic tests directly to consumers. In an interview, Jeffrey Shuren, head of FDA's medical-devices division, and Alberto Gutierrez, who oversees the FDA unit that regulates certain laboratory tests, said they considered direct-to-consumer genetic tests "high risk" and have already informed companies selling such tests through their websites that they must seek FDA approval.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: FDA Officials Not Sure Agency Will Approve Direct-To-Consumer Genetic Tests

#text: Advanced Digital Information Corp.

reported first-quarter earnings of $8.7 million, or 16 cents a share, 2 cents better than analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had anticipated. Last year, the company posted first-quarter earnings of $7.2 million, or 13 cents a share. Sales totaled $90.1 million, up 41 percent compared with the year-ago period. Revenue growth was attributed to OEM sales, which grew by nearly $20 million compared with the fourth-quarter total. Shares closed down 13 cents to $17.31.

#text: After the market closed Wednesday, Dow Chemical

said it has lowered its earnings outlook for the first quarter but didn't give a per share estimate. The company said lower earnings are the result of Dow taking into account the additional shares issued because of the close of its merger with Union Carbide. The company was also hurt by higher U.S. natural gas costs. Previously, the company expected first-quarter earnings between 25 cents and 40 cents a share. Analysts currently expect a profit of 26 cents a share. Shares closed down 4 cents to $31.40.

Headlines.Headline:
SmithKline to Sell Units for Nearly $2
Billion

PARAGRAPH.#text:
SmithKline Beecham
 announced it had
reached accords to sell its pharmacy-benefits and clinical-lab businesses
for nearly $2 billion, allowing the company to focus on its core drug
operations.

Headlines.Author: Michael Waldholz
Headlines.Headline: AIDS Strains Worry Researchers

PARAGRAPH.#text:
New AIDS strains
 resist combination
therapies, researchers are convinced. Several presentations at the AIDS
conference in Geneva show strains of HIV found in recently infected people
are able to resist treatment with the drug combinations that have
revolutionized the AIDS battle in the past two years.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: AIDS Strains Worry Researchers
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Headline: Laboratory Corp. Chief Resigns

PARAGRAPH.#text:
A senior
 executive of Laboratory
Corp. of America Holdings resigned as part of the company's recent
government settlement for fraudulently billing federal and state
health-care programs for unnecessary medical tests.

PARAGRAPH.#text:

million civil penalty for billing federal and state health-care programs
for unnecessary medical tests.

Headlines.Author: Linda Sandler
Headlines.Headline:
Consolidated Cigar
Lights Up With IPO

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Ronald Perelman
's Consolidated Cigar
Holdings, due to be rolled out in a few weeks despite the recent rockiness
of the market, will be the 10th stock created since the late 1980s from his
grab bag of debt-heavy companies.

Headlines.Author: Wendy Bounds
Headlines.Headline: Corning Spins Off Lab Units

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Corning will spin off
 its troubled laboratory-testing division. The move
follows the firm's failure to strike a deal to sell the $1.6 billion business.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Corning Spins Off Lab Units
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition

Headlines.Author: Susan Pulliam
Headlines.Headline:
Corning May Disappoint
Investor Michael Price

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Forget about RJR

Nabisco and Dial. Is Michael Price about to score a home
run with his investments in Laboratory Corp. and Corning?
Don't hold you breathe, say some analysts. His efforts to
push a deal between the companies seem to be failing.

Headlines.BodyHeadline:
Corning May Disappoint
Investor Michael Price
Headlines.Provider: The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition
